text: Engineering precursor metabolite pools for increasing production of antitumor mithramycins in Streptomyces argillaceus Daniel Zabala, Alfredo F. Braña, Ana B. Flórez, José A. Salas, Carmen Méndez n Departamento de Biología Funcional e Instituto Universitario de Oncología del Principado de Asturias (I.U.O.P.A), Universidad de Oviedo, Oviedo, Spain Article history: Received 11 June 2013 Received in revised form 24 July 2013 Accepted 3 October 2013 Available online 19 October 2013 Keywords: Streptomyces Metabolic engineering Glucose-1-phosphate Malonyl-CoA Antitumor Production Streptomyces are producers of a high variety of secondary metabolites with application in medicine, veterinary and agricul- ture such as antibiotics, immunosuppressant, antitumor and other bioactive compounds (Bérdy, 2005). Production yields of these metabolites by the natural producer strains are usually quite low, and consequently optimizing production is normally required for the development of these compounds as potentially useful drugs. This need is even more demanding in the case of bioactive compounds generated by combinatorial biosynthesis, which are generally produced at lower yields (Salas and Méndez, 2007). Improvement of production yields has been achieved by standard random mutagenesis followed by selection of better producing strains of the target compound. With the development of genetic engineering in Streptomyces and the increasing knowledge of biosynthetic pathways, increased production of these metabolites has been addressed by using more rational strategies such as 1096-7176/$ - see front matter & 2013 International Metabolic Engineering Society. Mithramycin (MTM) is a polyketide antitumor compound produced by Streptomyces argillaceus constituted by a tricyclic aglycone with two aliphatic side chains, a trisaccharide and a disaccharide chain. The biosynthesis of the polyketide aglycone is initiated by the condensation of ten malonyl-CoA units to render a carbon chain that is modiﬁed to a tetracyclic intermediate and sequentially glycosylated by ﬁve deoxysugars originated from glucose-1-phosphate. Further oxidation and reduction render the ﬁnal compound. We aimed to increase the precursor supply of malonyl-CoA and/or glucose-1-phosphate in S. argillaceus to enhance MTM production. We have shown that by overexpressing either the S. coelicolor phosphoglucomutase gene pgm or the acetyl-CoA carboxylase ovmGIH genes from the oviedomycin biosynthesis gene cluster in S. argillaceus, we were able to increase the intracellular pool of glucose-1-phosphate and malonyl-CoA, respectively. Moreover, we have cloned the S. argillaceus ADP- glucose pyrophosphorylase gene glgCa and the acyl-CoA:diacylglycerol acyltransferase gene aftAa, and we showed that by inactivating them, an increase of the intracellular concentration of glucose-1- phosphate/glucose-6-phosphate and malonyl-CoA/acetyl-CoA was observed, respectively. Each indivi- dual modiﬁcation resulted in an enhancement of MTM production but the highest production level was obtained by combining all strategies together. In addition, some of these strategies were successfully applied to increase production of four MTM derivatives with improved pharmacological proper- ties: demycarosyl-mithramycin, demycarosyl-3D-β-D-digitoxosyl-mithramycin, mithramycin SK and mithramycin SDK. & 2013 International Metabolic Engineering Society. metabolic engineering (Olano et al., 2008; Papagianni, 2012). Pathways for the biosyntheses of secondary metabolites use precursors synthesized during glycolysis, the tricarboxylic acid cycle and the pentose-phosphate pathway (Rokem et al., 2007). Supply of these precursors for the biosyntheses of secondary metabolites can be a bottleneck. Metabolic engineering has been applied to selected steps of primary metabolism in producer strains, to increase the intracellular pool of precursors and to redirect the ﬂux towards the biosynthesis of the desired metabo- lite (Olano et al., 2008). Thus, higher production of clavulanic acid was obtained by inactivating the glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase gap1 in S. clavuligerus (Li and Townsend, 2006). Similarly, deletion of the phosphofructokinase gene pfkA or the glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase genes zwf1 or zwf2 resulted in higher production of actinorhodin and undecylprodigiosin in S. coelicolor and/or S. lividans (Borodina et al., 2008; Butler et al., 2002; Ryu et al., 2006). Overexpression of genes for the biosynthesis of speciﬁc building blocks has been used as well as a strategy to produce higher amounts of speciﬁc secondary metabolites. By overexpressing the acetyl-CoA carboxylase genes in S. coelicolor or in Saccharomyces cerevisiae, higher amounts of actinorhodin or 6-methylsalicylic acid were obtained (Ryu et al., 2006; Wattanachaisaereekul et al., 2008) Fig. 1. Overview of the metabolic origin of mithramycin precursor metabolites. Engineered biosynthesis steps by overexpression and inactivation of the corresponding genes are indicated by thick arrows and by crossed arrows, respectively. ACC, acetyl-CoA carboxylase; DAG, diacylglycerol; PGM, phosphoglucomutase; TCA, tricarboxylic acid.

and by duplicating the methylmalonyl-CoA mutase operon in Sacchar- opolyspora erythraea an increase in erythromycin production was achieved (Reeves et al., 2007). Mithramycin (MTM) (Fig. 1) is an antitumor compound pro- duced by S. argillaceus and was approved for use as an anticancer drug in 1970 (Newman and Cragg, 2007). New MTM derivatives with high antitumor activity and/or less toxicity than the parental compound have been generated by using different strategies of combinatorial biosynthesis; these compounds are promising can- didates for development as new antitumor drugs (Baig et al., 2008; Núñez et al., 2012; Pérez et al., 2008; Remsing et al., 2003). MTM is a glycosylated polyketide synthesized by the condensation of ten malonyl-CoA units to render a carbon chain that is subsequently modiﬁed to originate a tetracyclic intermediate. This intermediate is sequentially glycosylated by ﬁve deoxysugars that in turn are synthesized from glucose-1-phosphate. Further oxidation and reduction steps render the ﬁnal compound (Lombó et al., 2006). Our aim is to increase the intracellular pool of glucose-1- phosphate and malonyl-CoA in S. argillaceus, to enhance produc- tion of MTM. We showed that by favoring their synthesis and/or by diverting away their use from other biosynthesis pathways, higher production of MTM was achieved. These strategies were applied to increase production of MTM derivatives with improved pharmacological properties. 2.1. Strains, culture conditions, and plasmids

Streptomyces argillaceus ATCC12956 (MTM producer) was used as host for gene expression and production. S. argillaceus M7W1 was used as host for production of mithramycin SK and mithra- mycin SDK (Remsing et al., 2003). Escherichia coli DH10B (Invitro- gen) was used as host for subcloning, and E. coli ET12567 (pUB307) (Kieser et al., 2000) was used as donor for intergeneric conjuga- tion. When plasmid-containing clones were grown, the medium was supplemented with the appropriate antibiotics: 5 or 25 μg/ml thiostrepton for liquid or solid cultures, respectively; 100 μg/ml ampicillin; 25 μg/ml apramycin; 25 μg/ml kanamycin; 25 μg/ml chloramphenicol; 25 μg/ml nalidixic acid and 200 μg/ml hygro- mycin. Plasmids pCR-blunt (Invitrogen), pUK21 (Vieira and Messing, 1991), pBSKT (Lombó et al., 1999), pIJ2925 (Janssen and Bibb, 1993), pIAGO (Aguirrezabalaga et al., 2000), and pHZ1358 (Sun et al., 2002), were used for subcloning. Plasmid pMP3nBII directs the biosynthesis of TDP-D-digitoxose (Pérez et al., 2006), and was used for producing demycarosyl-mithramycin and D. Zabala et al. / Metabolic Engineering 20 (2013) 187–197

demycarosyl-3D-β-D-digitoxosyl-mithramycin (Pérez et al., 2008). Plasmid pHyg (Olano et al., 2004) was used as source of the hygromycin resistance cassette. Cosmid cosAB4 (Lombó et al., 2004; Méndez et al., 2002), S. coelicolor M145 (Kieser et al., 2000) and S. argillaceus chromosomal DNAs were used as DNA templates. Plasmid preparations, restriction endonuclease digestions, and other DNA manipulations were carried out according to standard procedures for Streptomyces and for E. coli (Kieser et al., 2000; Sambrook and Russell, 2001). Preparation of Streptomyces proto- plasts, transformation, and intergeneric conjugation from E. coli ET12567 (pUB307) to S. argillaceus were performed as described by Kieser et al., 2000. Oligonucelotides used in ampliﬁcation reactions are listed in Table 1. PCR conditions were as follows: 100 ng of template DNA was mixed with 30 pmols of each oligonucleotide and 2 units of Pfx DNA Polymerase (Invitrogen), in a total reaction volume of 50 μL containing 0.2 mM of each deoxynucleoside triphosphate, 10 mM KCl, 10 mM (NH4)2SO4, 20 mM Tris–HCl (pH 8.8), 2 mM MgSO4, and 0.1% Triton X-100. The ampliﬁcation reactions were performed in a thermocycler (MyCycler Thermal Cycler System; Bio-Rad), using an initial denaturation step of 5 min at 95 1C, speciﬁc ampliﬁcation conditions are shown in Table 1, followed by an extension step of 10 min at 68 1C.

Expression of target genes under the control of the erythro- mycin resistance promoter (ermEp) in S. argillaceus strains was carried out using pIAGO. All constructs were introduced by protoplasts transformation into the corresponding strain and transformants were selected for thiostrepton resistance. pPGM: pgm (SCO7443) from S. coelicolor was ampliﬁed using oligonucleotides PgmF and Pgm3R (Table 1) and subcloned into pCR-blunt. This gene was recovered as a PstI-HindIII fragment (using these sites from the vector) and subcloned into the same sites of pIAGO. pGIH: an FspI-PagI fragment from cosAB4 containing the 3′-end of ovmF, ovmG, ovmI and ovmH genes was subcloned into pUK21 previously digested with SmaI and NcoI, generating pDZ1. This construct was digested with SanDI (end-ﬁlled with Klenow) and EcoRV, and religated to delete most of ovmF, generating pDZ2. Table 1 Oligonucleotides used in this study for PCR. Finally, an XbaI-SphI fragment from pDZ2 (using these sites from the vector) containing ovmG, ovmI and ovmH was recovered and subcloned into the same sites of pIAGO. pMIX: an XbaI-HindIII fragment from pGIH (using these sites from the vector) containing ovmG, ovmI and ovmH genes, was subcloned into the SpeI, HindIII sites of pPGM, downstream of pgm. 2.5. Cloning of glgCa and aftAa genes from S. argillaceus

glgCa: sequence comparisons of S. coelicolor GlgC (SCO0961) with similar proteins in data bases were used to design a pair of degenerate oligonucleotides (glgC1 and glgC3, Table 1) corre- sponding to two conserved regions of ADP-glucose pyrophosphor- ylases. These primers were used to amplify a 660 bp internal DNA region of glgCa from S. argillaceus. Sequence of ﬂanking DNA regions was obtained and the entire gene was cloned. aftAa: sequence comparisons of S. coelicolor AftA (SCO0958) with similar proteins in data bases were used to design two degenerate oligonucleotides (AftA F1 and AftA R1, Table 1) from conserved regions of acyl-CoA:diacylglycerol acyltransferases. These primers were used to amplify a 600 bp internal DNA region of aftAa from S. argillaceus. Sequencing of ﬂanking DNA regions was obtained and the entire gene was cloned. The DNA sequence of glgCa has been deposited at GenBank under accession no. HF953986, and the sequence of aftAa under accession no. HF953985. 2.6. Generation of mutants Several mutants were generated by inserting an antibiotic resistance cassette (apramycin or hygromycin) into the target gene.

S. argillaceus GLGC: a 1.8 kb DNA fragment from S. argillaceus containing the entire glgCa, and 420 bp and 300 bp from upstream and downstream regions respectively, was ampliﬁed using oligonu- cleotides glgc-AF and glgc-AR (Table 1). This fragment was sub- cloned into pCR-blunt, and recovered as an EcoRI fragment (using these sites from the vector) and subcloned into the same site of pBSKT, generating pBSKT-glgC. An EcoRV-SmaI fragment containing the aac(3)-IV gene was introduced in the same direction of tran- scription, into the blunt ended NcoI site of pBSKT-glgC generating pBSKTA-glgC. The disrupted glgCa gene was rescued from this plasmid as an XbaI-EcoRV fragment (using these sites from the vector) and subcloned into the XbaI, SmaI sites of pIJ2925. The insert was recovered as a BglII fragment (using these sites from the vector) and subcloned into the BamHI site of pHZ1358, generating the ﬁnal construct pHZ1358A-glgC. S. argillaceus AFTA: a 1.3 kb DNA fragment containing the 5′- end of aftAa was ampliﬁed using oligonucleotides AftA-Efor and AftA-Erev (Table 1) and subcloned in pCR-blunt, generating pblunt-TAGE. The 930 bp XhoI (using this site from the vector)- NcoI fragment was recovered and subcloned into the same sites of pUK21, generating pUKTAGE. On the other hand, a 1.5 kb DNA fragment containing the 3′-end of aftAa was ampliﬁed using oligonucleotides AftA-Afor and AftA-Arev (Table 1) and subcloned into pCR-blunt, generating pblunt-TAGA. The 1.5 bp XbaI-SpeI fragment from this construct was recovered and subcloned in the desired orientation, into the XbaI site of pUKTAGE, generating pUKTAGAE. The NheI-SpeI fragment from pHyg containing a hygromycin resistance cassette was subcloned in the right orienta- tion into the XbaI site of pUKTAGAE, generating pUKTAGAEH. Finally, the truncated aftAa gene was rescued as a SpeI fragment, end-ﬁlled with Klenow and subcloned into the BamHI site (end- ﬁlled with Klenow) of pHZ1358, generating pHZTAGAEH. This plasmid was introduced into S. argillaceus and hygromycin-resis- tant, thiostrepton-sensitive colonies were selected. S. argillaceus GLGC-AFTA: to generate this double mutant, pHZTA- GAEH was introduced into S. argillaceus GLGC, and hygromycin- resistant, thiostrepton-sensitive transconjugants were selected. 2.7. Mithramycin production and growth determinations

MTM production was analyzed in R5A (Fernández et al., 1998) liquid and solid medium. Cultures in solid medium were carried out in 25-compartment squared Petri plates containing 3 mL of R5A medium per compartment, each inoculated with 20 mL of a spore suspension (106 spores/mL). After 8 days of incubation at 30 1C, the agar was extracted twice with a solution of ethyl acetate and 1% formic acid. The organic extracts were evaporated under vacuum and suspended in 200 mL of DMSO:methanol (50:50). Samples (2 mL) were analyzed by reversed phase chromatography in an Acquity UPLC equipment with a BEH C18 column (1.7 μm, 2.1 (cid:1) 100 mm2, Waters), with acetonitrile and 0.1% triﬂuoroacetic acid as mobile phase. Samples were eluted with 10% acetonitrile for 1 min, followed by a linear gradient from 10% to 80% acetoni- trile in 7 min, at a ﬂow rate of 0.5 mL/min and column tempera- ture of 35 1C. Detection and spectral characterization was performed by photodiode array detection and Empower software (Waters). MTM concentration was estimated by calculating peak areas and comparing them with known concentrations of MTM. For MTM production in liquid medium, strains were grown in a two-step culture method. A seed culture was prepared in 10 mL of Trypticase Soy Broth medium inoculated with 100 ml of spores (106 spores/mL). After incubation for 24 h at 30 1C and 250 rpm, this culture was used to inoculate 250 mL Erlenmeyer ﬂasks each containing 50 mL of R5A at an optical density of 0.2 at 600 nm. Production of MTM was monitored daily for 8 days. Culture samples of 500 mL were extracted and processed as described above for MTM determination. In parallel, S. argillaceus growth was monitored by determining intracellular DNA concentration of 500 mL samples following the method described by Burton (1956). Three

For each time point, three cultures of 50 mL of R5A were inoculated with the corresponding strain as described in the previous section. Samples of 500 mL were harvested and used to Fig. 2. determine MTM production and quantiﬁcation of intracellular DNA. The remaining culture was ﬁltered and the mycelium was suspended in 1 mL of ice-cold 6% perchloric acid. The mixture was shaken using a vortex mixer for 1 min and then centrifuged at 12,000 rpm to collect the supernatant. After taking 10 mL of supernatant for acetyl-CoA and malonyl-CoA determinations (see below), the remaining solution was neutralized drop by drop with 300 mL of 3 M K2CO3 and then centrifuged. Samples of 100 mL of supernatant were used to determine glucose-1-phosphate and glucose-6-phosphate concentration as described by Bergmeyer et al. (1984). Pure samples of glucose-1-phosphate and glucose- 6-phosphate were used as standards. Acetyl-CoA and malonyl-CoA were determined by HPLC-MS, using a modiﬁcation of the method described by Dalluge et al. (2002). Samples (10 μL) were analyzed using an Atlantis T3 column (3 μm, 2.1 (cid:1) 150 mm2, Waters). The mobile phase was acetonitrile with 0.5% acetic acid (solvent A) and 25 mM ammonium acetate with 0.5% acetic acid (solvent B). Elution was performed with a linear gradient from 0 to 30% of solvent A in 15 min, followed by 100% solvent A for 5 min and re-equilibration to initial conditions for 10 min, at a ﬂow rate of 0.2 mL/min. The compounds were detected by selected ion record- ing of the corresponding protonated ions (m/z 810.2 for acetyl-CoA and m/z 854.2 for malonyl-CoA). Instrumental parameters for MS detection were as detailed by Dalluge et al. (2002). Pure samples of acetyl-CoA and malonyl-CoA were used as standards. 3.1. to enhance mithramycin production

MTM contains ﬁve deoxysugars that are synthesized through speciﬁc enzymatic steps of the MTM pathway, using as precursor glucose-1-phosphate (Lombó et al., 1997) (Fig. 1). This metabo- Increasing the intracellular pool of glucose-1-phosphate D. Zabala et al. / Metabolic Engineering 20 (2013) 187–197 lite in turn is synthesized from glucose-6-phosphate through a reversible reaction catalyzed by phosphoglucomutase (Pgm). On the other hand, glucose-1-phosphate is also used as a precursor in the biosynthesis of glucose-based polymers and the biosynthesis of cell wall components. To improve MTM production in S. argillaceus we decided to increase the intracellular pool of glucose-1-phosphate and to channel it towards the MTM pathway by (i) favoring its biosynthesis, and (ii) diminishing its use in the biosynthesis of carbohydrate storage compounds.

To favor the biosynthesis of glucose-1-phosphate, we over- expressed the phosphoglucomutase encoding gene sco7443 from S. coelicolor (Ryu et al., 2006) in S. argillaceus. This gene was cloned into the multicopy plasmid pIAGO under the control of ermEp, and the resultant plasmid pPGM was introduced into S. argillaceus to generate S. argillaceus PGM. To investigate whether this strain accumulated higher amounts of glucose-1-phosphate, intracellular concentration of this metabolite and of glucose-6-phosphate was determined at 24, 36 and 48 h in cultures of S. argillaceus PGM grown in R5A liquid medium. Cultures of S. argillaceus IAGO (control containing pIAGO) were grown and analyzed in parallel. As observed in Fig. 2, overexpression of pgm led to an increase of the intracellular concentration of glucose-1-phosphate (15%–34%; Fig. 2A) and to a decrease of glucose-6-phosphate (6%–61%; Fig. 2B), indicating that glucose-6-phosphate was efﬁciently con- verted into glucose-1-phosphate in S. argillaceus PGM. The accu- mulation of glucose-1-phosphate implies a reduction of carbon ﬂux through the glycolytic pathway and consequently a decrease in the biosynthesis of acetyl- and malonyl-CoA, so the intracellular pool of these metabolites in S. argillaceus PGM was evaluated and compared to the control strain. As anticipated a reduction in the concentration of both metabolites was detected (26%–51% for malonyl-CoA, and 21%–39% for acetyl-CoA) (data not shown). To determine the effect of overexpression of pgm in MTM production, samples from cultures of both strains were analyzed for MTM production over the course of several days (Fig. 3A). While growth

These differences were reduced along time reaching a ﬁnal increase in MTM production of approximately 9%.

Glucose-1-phosphate can also be used as precursor for the biosynthesis of oligo- and polysaccharides, involving its activation as a NDP (nucleoside-diphospho)-glucose by different NDP- glucose pyrophosphorylases. In order to increase glucose-1- phosphate availability for MTM production, we decided to inacti- vate the ADP-glucose pyrophosphorylase gene of S. argillaceus to block the biosynthesis of ADP-glucose. In S. coelicolor, this enzyme and its coding gene glgC (sco0961) have been cloned and char- acterized (Asención Diez et al., 2012; Martin et al., 1997). In order to clone the homologous gene from S. argillaceus, we compared the amino acid sequence of GlgC (SCO0961) from S. coelicolor with other proteins in data bases to design a pair of oligonucleotides to amplify glgC- homologous genes. Using these primers, a 660 bp PCR product from S. argillaceus was obtained. Sequencing of ﬂanking DNA regions allowed the identiﬁcation a 1.8 kb BamHI fragment containing the entire ADP-glucose pyrophosphorylase gene (named glgCa), which encodes a protein highly similar to SCO0961 from S. coelicolor (93% identity), and 420 bp upstream and 300 bp downstream regions. This fragment was used to generate a glgCa deﬁcient mutant by inserting an apramycin resistance cassette in the gene in the same direction of transcrip- tion, and by replacing the wild type copy of the chromosome of S. argillaceus by the mutated one. The resultant mutant S. argillaceus GLGC was veriﬁed by PCR, ampliﬁcation fragments of 1.8 kb and 3.4 kb were obtained from the wild type strain and from S. argillaceus GLGC respectively, using glgC-AF and glgC-AR as primers (Fig. 4A). This result conﬁrmed that in S. argillaceus GLGC the replacement event had occurred

from the wild type strain and from S. argillaceus GLGC respectively, using glgC-AF and glgC-AR as primers (Fig. 4A). This result conﬁrmed that in S. argillaceus GLGC the replacement event had occurred. To determine if this mutation affected the intracellular concentration of glucose-1-phosphate, the concentration of this metabolite and glucose-6-phosphate were quantiﬁed and compared to the wild type strain (Fig. 2C and D): concentration of both, glucose-1-phosphate and glucose- 6-phosphate increased in the mutant compared to the wild type strain (29%–46% for the ﬁrst, and 13%–45% for the latter). More- over, there was a signiﬁcant increase of the concentration of acetyl-CoA in the mutant (up to 70% at 24 h), while the increase of the concentration of malonyl-CoA was lower (7%–15%) (data not shown). These changes were reﬂected in higher amount of MTM production in cultures of the mutant in relation to the wild type strain: about 50% more MTM at 3 days of growth, and ﬁnal production about 22% higher (Fig. 3B). No differences in growth were observed along the fermentation (data not shown).

To favor the biosynthesis of malonyl-CoA, an ACC was over- expressed in S. argillaceus. Most ACC from actinomycetes are constituted by three subunits (α,β and ε) encoded by accA2, accB and accE, generally located at the chromosome (Diacovich et al., 2002; Gago et al., 2011; Rodríguez et al., 2001). In addition, some polyketide gene clusters contain paralogous genes within the clusters that can be involved in providing malonyl-CoA for the biosynthesis of polyketide moieties. The oviedomycin gene cluster contains (ovmG and ovmH) coding for proteins that are very similar to β- and α-chains of ACC, respectively (Lombó et al., 2004; Méndez et al., 2002). A deeper analysis of the oviedomycin DNA sequence showed the presence of a third gene (named ovmI) between ovmG and ovmH that would code for a putative ε-chain of the ACC (54% identity to SCLAV4485 from S. clavuligerus). Since all the ACC coding genes of the oviedomycin gene cluster were contiguous and transcribed in the same direction, we decided to use them to overproduce an ACC in S. argillaceus, and therefore to increase the concentration of malonyl-CoA. These three genes were cloned in pIAGO and the resultant plasmid pGIH was used to transform S. argillaceus. In order to determine if the intracellular pool of recombinant strain malonyl-CoA increased in the resultant S. argillaceus GIH, this metabolite and the concentration of acetyl-CoA were quantiﬁed and compared to S. argillaceus IAGO, as a control strain. As can be observed in Fig. 5, overexpression of ovmGIH led to an increase of the intracellular concentration of malonyl-CoA (117% at 24 h and 360% at 48 h; Fig. 5A), and a decrease of the acetyl-CoA pool at early fermentation times, indicating a progressive conversion of

D. Zabala et al. / Metabolic Engineering 20 (2013) 187–197 investigated if the increase in malonyl-CoA had any effect on MTM production. As observed in Fig. 6A, S. argillaceus GIH produced higher amounts of MTM at 4 days of fermentation and thereafter, with yields around 35% higher at 4 days of incubation and a ﬁnal yield around 21% higher. Malonyl- and acetyl-CoA are also precursors for the biosynth- esis of TAG, a carbon storage compound widespread among actinomycetes (Alvarez and Steinbüchel, 2002). Therefore we decided to interfere with the biosynthesis of TAG in an attempt to increase the intracellular concentration of those metabolites and consequently MTM production. The ﬁnal step in TAG bio- synthesis is a reaction consisting on the esteriﬁcation of diacylgly- cerol with a fatty acid molecule. In S. coelicolor, the enzyme catalyzing this step (an acyl-CoA:diacylglycerol acyltransferase) and its coding gene aftA (sco0958) have been identiﬁed (Arabolaza et al., 2008). To clone the homologous gene from S. argillaceus, we compared SCO0958 with other proteins in data-bases and design oligonucleotides from two conserved regions of these proteins. Using these primers, a single DNA fragment of 600 bp was ampliﬁed from S. argillaceus DNA. Further sequencing of the DNA ﬂanking regions allowed to obtain the entire sequence of this gene, named aftAa, which coded for a protein highly similar to acyl-CoA:diacylglycerol acyltransferase-like proteins (77% and 78% identity to SCO0958 from S. coelicolor and SAV7256 from S. avermitilis, respectively), and containing the conserved motif “HHALADG” (Kalscheuer et al., 2007). This gene was inactivated by deleting a 300 bp internal fragment, which was replaced by a hygromycin resistance cassette lacking the transcriptional termi- nator and cloned in the same direction of transcription. The resultant strain S. argillaceus AFTA was veriﬁed by PCR: using oligonucleotides Afta-MF1 and AFTA-Arev, a 2.2 kb PCR fragment was ampliﬁed from the wild type strain, while a fragment of 3.4 kb was obtained from the mutant (Fig. 4B). For a further improvement of MTM production, we decided to increase intracellular concentrations of glucose-1-phosphate and malonyl-CoA simultaneously, using different approaches. Firstly, we tested overexpressing ovmGIH or pgm in strains S. argillaceus GLGC and S. argillaceus AFTA. In both cases, an increase in MTM production was obtained in comparison to control strains, but while S. argillaceus GLGC-GIH produced 63% more than the control strain, S. argillaceus AFTA-PGM only increased MTM production by 17%, less than the yield obtained with S. argillaceus AFTA-GIH (Table 2). Then, we decided to overexpress together both set of genes in each mutant. Plasmid pMIX was generated by subcloning ovmGIH downstream of pgm in pPGM. After expressing pMIX in the mutants, a further increase in MTM production was obtained in each case in comparison to control strains (Table 2): these strains produced approximately a 7% more MTM than any other recombinant strain derived from S. argillaceus GLGC or S. argilla- ceus AFTA (Table 2).

Finally, since the highest improvement in MTM production had been achieved by disrupting either glgCa or aftAa, we decided to generate a double mutant affected in both genes by replacing the wild type copy of aftAa by a mutated one in S. argillaceus GLGC. The resultant double mutant was apramycin and hygromycin resistant and was conﬁrmed by PCR analysis: using primers AftA-MF1 and AftA-Arev a 2.2 kb PCR fragment was ampliﬁed from S. argillaceus GLGC, while a 3.4 kb DNA fragment was obtained from the double mutant S. argillaceus GLGC-AFTA, con- ﬁrming the replacement event in the chromosome (Fig. 4C). As shown in Fig. 7A, MTM production started earlier and was higher all along the fermentation of S. argillaceus GLGC-AFTA in compar- ison to the wild type strain, with a ﬁnal yield 125% higher. Secondary metabolites are synthesized using primary metabo- lites originated by central carbon pathways as precursors. In the MTM biosynthesis pathway ﬁve glucose-1-phosphates that in turn are originated from glucose-6-phosphate, and ten malonyl-CoA units derived from acetyl-CoA, are used to synthesize the MTM molecule. The availability of these precursors can be a bottleneck for MTM production and of important derivatives generated by combinatorial biosynthesis. We have applied metabolic engineer- ing to the producer of MTM S. argillaceus in order to increase its precursor metabolites (i.e. glucose-1-phosphate and malonyl-CoA) and therefore to enhance MTM production. Two approaches were used to increase glucose-1-phosphate: overexpression of the phosphoglucomutase gene pgm from S. coelicolor, and inactivation of the S. argillaceus ADP-glucose pyrophosphorylase gene glgCa. The ﬁrst approach led to an increase of glucose-1-phosphate and to a reduction of glucose-6-phosphate along with a decrease of malonyl- and acetyl-CoA. This result suggests that Pgm is convert- ing glucose-6-phosphate into glucose-1-phosphate, but by doing so the carbon ﬂux through the glycolysis and/or pentose- phosphate pathways was reduced, and as a consequence the intracellular pool of acetyl-CoA and malonyl-CoA diminished. So, overexpression of pgm had a positive effect enhancing the MTM precursor glucose-1-phophate, but it also had a negative effect by decreasing the pool of the other precursor malonyl-CoA. To follow the second approach, a homologous gene to glgC (Martin et al.,

In order to enhance the intracellular concentration of malonyl- CoA, two strategies were also followed: overexpression of the ACC genes ovmGIH from the oviedomycin gene cluster of S. antibioticus, and inactivation of the S. argillaceus acyl-CoA:diacylglycerol acyl- transferase gene aftAa. To overexpress the ACC genes, we used the oviedomycin biosynthesis genes ovmGIH that code for a putative ACC, since these three genes were located together in the chromo- some and not separately as it normally occurs in Streptomyces (Lombó et al., 2004; Rodríguez et al., 2001). Expression of these genes in S. argillaceus led to a signiﬁcant increase in malonyl-CoA, and to a moderate decrease in acetyl-CoA, which conﬁrmed that ovmGIH coded for an active ACC. To follow the second approach, it was required to clone a homologous gene to aftA (Arabolaza et al., 2008) from S. argillaceus and then to inactivate it. The resultant mutant strain accumulated higher amounts of both malonyl-CoA and acetyl-CoA. This indicated that by blocking aftAa, the pool of acetyl-CoA and malonyl-CoA can be increased. The effect of increasing the intracellular pool of MTM precursors was an increase of MTM production both in liquid cultures and on solid medium. However, MTM production levels were different depending on the strategy used: (i) those strategies diverting away the use of MTM precursors from other pathways proved to be more efﬁcient to improve MTM production than those favoring their biosynthesis; and (ii) higher production of MTM was obtained by applying strategies to enhance malonyl-CoA than to increase glucose-1-phosphate. This suggests that in S. argillaceus, the avail- ability of malonyl-CoA is lower than of glucose-1-phosphate for MTM production. In a similar way, higher concentrations of malonyl- CoA have been also correlated to better production yields of the non-glycosylated polyketide oxytetracycline in S. rimosus (Tang et al., 2011) and higher production of actinorhodin has been reported by independently overexpressing an ACC or by inactivating the aftA gene in S. coelicolor (Arabolaza et al., 2008; Ryu et al., 2006). However, contrary to what is shown here, no apparent change was reported in actinorhodin production when glgC was inactivated in the same producer strain (Martin et al., 1997). On the other hand, several unsuccessful attempts for increasing antibiotic production by metabolic engineering have been reported. Actinorhodin production was not enhanced but rather reduced by deleting pgm in S. coelicolor (Ryu et al., 2006). Also, lower production of tetracenomycin was observed in a S. cinnamonensis C730.1 mutant affected in the crotonyl-CoA reductase gene (Li et al., 2009).

Most approaches to increase production of secondary metabo- lites in Streptomyces have involved altering a single step in primary metabolism (Olano et al., 2008; Papagianni, 2012). However, we showed here that combining different strategies in the same strain is better than using a single strategy to improve MTM production. Thus, by (i) combining strategies leading to increase one precursor, either glucose-1-phophate (i.e. overexpression of Pgm in mutant S. argillaceus GLGC) or malonyl-CoA (i.e. overexpression of ACC in mutant S. argillaceus AFTA), or (ii) combining strategies for increas- ing the pool of both precursors at the same time (i.e. overexpression of Pgm, ACC or both, in S. argillaceus AFTA, S. argillaceus GLGC, or S. argillaceus GLGC-AFTA mutants), further enhancements in MTM production were achieved. Therefore, by introducing the four genetic modiﬁcations to a single strain we could generate the best MTM producer strain (S. argillaceus GLGC-AFTA-MIX), which pro- duced approximately 3.3 and 4.7 times more MTM than the wild type strain in liquid and solid media, respectively.

These metabolic engineering strategies were also applied to improve production of new MTM derivatives obtained by combi- natorial biosynthesis, which showed higher antitumor activity and/or less toxicity than the parental compound, being potential antitumor drugs (Albertini et al., 2006; Baig et al., 2008; Núñez et al., 2012; Pérez et al., 2008; Remsing et al., 2003). Higher production was achieved for these new derivatives (between 92% and 374%) by increasing the intracellular pool of MTM precursors. Again, the best results were obtained when the availability of both precursors was increased at the same time. Most of these new MTM derivatives are produced as a mixture of compounds by the original recombinant strain, and in some cases, together with the parental compound that generally is produced in higher yields. The engi- neered strains described in this work showed an additional improve- ment: target compounds were produced in higher proportion than MTM (i.e. production of demycarosyl-mithramycin and demycarosyl- 3D-β-D-digitoxosyl-mithramycin accounted for a 38% of total mithra- mycins produced by the original strain S. argillaceus-pMP3*BII, while they accounted for a 60% when produced by the engineered strain S. argillaceus GLGC-AFTA-pMP3nBII). In conclusion, we were able to increase the intracellular pool of glucose-1-phosphate in S. argillaceus, by overexpressing the S. coelico- lor phosphoglucomutase gene pgm or by inactivating S. argillaceus ADP-glucose pyrophosphorylase gene glgCa, being the second

approach better to improve MTM production. On the other hand, we were also able to increase the intracellular pool of malonyl-CoA, by overexpressing the acetyl-CoA carboxylase ovmGIH genes from the oviedomycin biosynthesis gene cluster or by inactivating the acyl-CoA: diacylglycerol acyltransferase gene aftAa, being the latter strategy better for improving MTM production. Each manipulation led to an increase in MTM production, obtaining the highest production by combining the four strategies in the same strain. In addition, metabolic engineering was successfully applied to increase production of four MTM derivatives generated by combinatorial biosynthesis, which showed higher antitumor activities or less toxicity than the parent compound.
